{"key":"processedPost-11013665","value":{"id":11013665,"first":11013390,"last":11013690,"when":1252336154,"utime":"09/07/09 06:09 PM","content":"<img src='/forums/images/moved.gif'> <b>This thread was moved from Advanced Mycology.</b><br /><br />Reason:<br />A simple fact of physics is that dirty water, such as that in your grain bag can't exist above 212F/100C in a liquid state.&nbsp; That means that as soon as it's heated above that level(required for sterilization) it will turn to steam and evaporate, either through the filter patch or through exploding the bag itself.&nbsp; That's why we use pressure cookers.<br />RR","title":"Re: sterilisation of grain bags using a microwave (moved)"}}